;;; RULES.slat — science-objects/ (graph-of-science) subcollection rules
;;; Sibling to graph-of-brand/, graph-of-store/, graph-of-life/, graph-of-world/,
;;; graph-of-person/, graph-of-institution/, graph-of-cultural-work/,
;;; graph-of-art-movement/, graph-of-event/ inside objects/.

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura") :note "Rules apply to both dialects.")

(rules
  :collection      "graph-of-science"
  :version         "1.0.0"
  :created         "2026-07-16"
  :owner           "Alfred"
  :parent-rules    "/Users/alfred/code/curator/objects/RULES.slat"

  :purpose
  "Structured knowledge about the SCIENCES — the durable content of what
   humans have figured out about how the world works. Physical laws,
   phenomena, forces, particles, chemical elements + compounds, cells,
   biological processes, anatomical systems, diseases, mathematical
   objects, statistical concepts, computing concepts, astronomical bodies,
   Earth-science phenomena. When a customer message mentions
   'photosynthesis' or 'entropy' or 'the Krebs cycle', this graph resolves
   it — canonical name, discipline, one-line what-it-is, cross-refs to
   the person who first described it and the institution that hosted the
   work."

  :shape
  "FACETED CLASSIFICATION (Ranganathan + schema.org/Thing + type-theory
   descent). Each science node is ONE record with typed attribute-facets.
   Facets declared in FACETS.slat; values enumerated per-facet. No
   sub-tree explosion. No per-experiment nodes. No per-paper nodes (that
   would be a separate graph-of-paper for a v2 lane)."

  :the-80-percent-rule
  "Per the 2026-07-16 design pivot (mailbox §16): 80% coverage of
   science-space, not 100%. Target: 3,000-8,000 canonical science
   nodes. Breakdown budget:
     ~200 physics laws + principles
     ~500 physical phenomena
     ~100 forces + fields
     ~200 particles (fundamental + composite + atomic + molecular kinds)
     ~120 chemical elements
     ~500-1000 common chemicals + compounds
     ~200 cell types
     ~500 biological processes
     ~100 anatomy systems + organs
     ~500 diseases (notable)
     ~500 mathematical objects
     ~200 statistical / probability concepts
     ~500 computing concepts
     ~500 astronomical bodies + phenomena
     ~300 Earth-science phenomena
   Total ceiling ~6,420 target; overshoot fine, undershoot fine."

  :no-fabrication
  "HARD RULE. Every scientific claim is provenanced. Preferred sources:
   Wikidata QID (CC0), Wikipedia URL (CC-BY-SA), OpenStax textbook chapter
   ref, PubMed MeSH term ID (biomedical, public), NIST reference data
   (physics constants). If the record was authored fresh at this lane
   without a specific source, mark :provenance :authored-by
   'graph-of-science-lane' and note that the fact is textbook-common
   knowledge that any freshman course covers. Do NOT invent equations,
   dates, discoverers, or particle properties. Missing is honest; wrong
   is not."

  :superseded-science-preserved
  "Historical scientific frameworks that have been REPLACED remain in
   the graph as first-class nodes with :status :superseded. Examples:
   phlogiston, luminiferous aether, caloric theory, geocentric model,
   the four humors, Ptolemaic epicycles, Lamarckian inheritance, the
   fixed-continents model. Their record carries:
     (:status :superseded)
     (:superseded-by <id-of-replacing-node>)
     (:era-dominant :year-from ... :year-to ...)
   These aren't errors to erase — they are how the sciences learned to
   check themselves. A kid who never heard of phlogiston can't
   understand why oxygen mattered."

  :contested-science-source-cites-both-sides
  "Where a live scientific debate is present (specific evolutionary
   details, specific climate-attribution numbers, specific quantum-
   interpretation choices), the node CITES the mainstream position AND
   the notable minority position, both with :provenance. Do NOT pick
   a side. Do NOT flatten disagreement into false consensus. Sakura's
   answer to a customer question about a contested topic is 'the
   mainstream view is X and Y is a well-known alternative; both come
   with these caveats'."

  :synonym-minimum
  "Every science node carries MINIMUM 3 synonyms. Includes: historical
   names (e.g., 'consumption' for tuberculosis, 'quicksilver' for
   mercury), common-vs-formal name (e.g., 'water' vs 'H₂O' vs
   'dihydrogen monoxide'), at least one non-English translation
   (mathematical + physics terms often have canonical German or French
   originals), common abbreviations (DNA / ATP / SSRI / etc). Aim for
   5-10 where the concept has multi-language history."

  :cross-graph-references-not-duplication
  "Science-nodes reference other graphs via :ref-graph:
     :first-described-by-ref  → graph-of-person (Newton, Curie, Darwin)
     :first-described-in-ref  → graph-of-cultural-work (Principia, Origin)
     :hosted-at-ref           → graph-of-institution (Cavendish Lab)
     :in-place-ref            → graph-of-world (Chernobyl, Mauna Loa)
     :appears-in-event-ref    → graph-of-event (1919 eclipse, Manhattan Project)
     :used-in-store-ref       → graph-of-store (mercury → thermometers, silica → semiconductors)
   Neither graph duplicates the other's content. Resolution failures
   return :ref-unresolved gracefully."

  :provenance-mandatory
  "Every science node carries :provenance with the source. Wikidata QID
   preferred (CC0). Wikipedia URL secondary (CC-BY-SA acknowledged in
   NOTICE below). OpenStax chapter refs OK (CC-BY 4.0). Manual authoring
   OK for freshman-textbook material but must be tagged :authored-by
   'graph-of-science-lane'."

  :license-conservative
  "SOURCES USED:
     - Wikidata (CC0 — public domain, we cite QIDs for verifiability)
     - Wikipedia (CC-BY-SA 3.0/4.0 — attribution + share-alike;
       we cite article URLs; derivative work licensing preserved)
     - OpenStax textbooks (CC-BY 4.0 — attribution required, preserved
       in :provenance)
     - PubMed MeSH (US government work, public domain for terminology)
     - NIST Reference Data (public, US government work)
     - Publicly-visible curriculum standards (NGSS, AP frameworks — the
       taxonomy names, not the assessment items)
   SOURCES NOT USED:
     - Any paywalled encyclopedia article
     - Any journal article behind a paywall
     - Any dataset without a clear public/permissive license
     - Any proprietary textbook prose"

  :no-corporate-names-in-nodes
  "Per curator repo lock: banned tokens in prose (Claude/Anthropic/OpenAI/
   Sonnet/Opus/Qwen/Llama/Mistral/Gemini). This graph deals in the
   commons of science. Where a technique was named after a company
   (rare in pure science — mostly happens in engineering/computing), use
   the generic name. E.g., 'PageRank' → 'eigenvector-centrality-ranking'
   in canonical name, with 'PageRank' as a synonym only where the
   history-of-computing context requires it."

  :never-name-drop-in-persona-prose
  "The science NODE carries the canonical scientist name — nodes are
   data, not dialogue. Sakura's persona voice says 'the naturalist
   who proposed heritable variation' — the graph resolves to
   'graph-of-person/darwin-charles'. Analysis sections in scheme-books
   MAY use full names when discussing history-of-science. Persona
   dialogue does not."

  :append-only
  "Once landed, this graph grows by APPEND (new nodes, new edges,
   new synonyms). When a paradigm shifts, add a new node and mark the
   old one :superseded-by; do not rewrite the old. Words don't change;
   the graph doesn't either. Alfred 2026-07-16."

  :files-in-this-collection
  ((:name "RULES.slat"                :purpose "this file — collection rules")
   (:name "README.slat"               :purpose "orientation for new authors")
   (:name "MANIFEST.slat"             :purpose "manifest of counts + subject breakdown")
   (:name "FACETS.slat"               :purpose "attribute-facet schema — declares all facets, value types, enumerated value lists")
   (:name "GRAPH-OF-SCIENCE-1.0.slat" :purpose "main flat file — one (science ...) record per entry, plus intra-graph (edge ...) records")
   (:name "SYNONYMS-INDEX.slat"       :purpose "lookup from any name variant → canonical science id")
   (:name "CROSS-REFS.slat"           :purpose "cross-graph edges — science → person/institution/place/event/work"))

  :notice
  "This collection incorporates content derived from Wikipedia articles
   (CC-BY-SA 3.0/4.0). Derivative science records preserve source URLs
   in :provenance and inherit CC-BY-SA licensing where derived from
   Wikipedia. Records derived solely from Wikidata inherit CC0. Records
   citing OpenStax inherit CC-BY 4.0. Records authored fresh at the
   graph-of-science lane are dedicated to the public domain under CC0."

  :non-blocking-caveats
  "1. schema.org has no clean vocabulary for scientific concepts; our
      facet vocabulary is bespoke to this graph.
   2. Wikidata coverage of the sciences is deep for well-known concepts,
      thinner for specialty terms. Expect 90%+ of top-1000 nodes to have
      a Wikidata QID; long tail may need OpenStax or textbook-authored
      records.
   3. Contested classifications (is Pluto a planet? is a virus alive?)
      appear as multi-value :classification facets, not as flame wars.
   4. Mathematical objects that admit multiple equivalent definitions
      (a group can be defined via axioms OR via Cayley tables) list
      both in :mathematical-form; either is a valid definition.")
